      <title><![CDATA[Ep.1 Pūkana a curator’s tale]]></title>
      <link>https://natlib.govt.nz/blog/posts/ep-1-pukana-a-curators-tale</link>
      <description><![CDATA[Listen to a conversation with Paul Diamond one of the curators of the Pūkana exhibition. We talk about developing the exhibition, what he learnt about curating exhibitions and the joy of working in a team.
      
      <p>From Porgy and Bess to haka, to Elsdon Best and Tuini Ngāwai, the Pūkana exhibition ranges far and wide to give a sense of the ihi, wehi and wana, inherent to Māori performance.</p>
      <h3>Find out more about Pūkana. </h3>
      <p><a href="/visiting/wellington/pukana-exhibition">Pūkana exhibition page</a> — includes resources about Māori perfomance.</p>
      <p><a href="/visiting/wellington/pukana-exhibition/pukana-curators-talk/origin-stories">Audio tour of exhibition</a> —  Pūkana — curator's talk.</p>
      <p><a href="https://newzealandhistory.podbean.com/e/pukanamoments-in-maori-performance/">Public history lecture</a> — Paul Diamond’s public talk about the exhibition content. </p>
      <h3>Acknowlegement</h3>
      <p>Thanks to Taita College Polygroup for allowing us to use their performance of ‘Kotiro Māori E’.</p>
      <h3>Music references</h3>
      <p>You heard the following music in this Library Loudhailer podcast. </p>
      <p>Intro theme song — <a href="/records/40685086">‘Funiculi Funicula’</a> the final track on from Keil Isles album ‘Take Off’.</p>
      <p>Outro — ‘Kotiro Māori E’  performed by Taita College Polygroup at the opening of the Pūkana exhbition. Used with permission. </p>
      <p><i>A transcript of this episode is available at <a href="https://natlib.govt.nz/blog/posts/ep-1-pukana-a-curators-tale">https://natlib.govt.nz/blog/posts/ep-1-pukana-a-curators-tale</a>.</i></p>]]></description>
